{
  "text": "Since the delayed recovery of pH has been given so much importance, the question arises: is acidic perfusion protective in early reperfusion? The answer is yes: brief acidosis in early reperfusion (BAER) is as protective as postconditioning. However, some concerns derive from the possibility that it might increase arrhythmias [CITATION_1] . This observation might be species-specific and is in contrast with the strong anti-arrhythmic effect of postconditioning obtained with intermittent reperfusion/ischemia. In fact, acidic reperfusion reduces the incidence of ventricular fibrillation in rat heart models of regional ischemia [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , and there are early reports which propose brief intermittent I/R as a maneuver against ventricular arrhythmias in reperfusion in different species [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , including pigs [CITATION_7] and humans [CITATION_8] . The ROS-dependent protection of BAER has been also demonstrated by Downey Group [CITATION_9] . We have also confirmed that BAER is protective and that this protection can be avoided by a ROS scavenger [CITATION_10] . Moreover, we have shown that in postconditioning and acidosis, the reaction of NOÁ with ROS to form RNS switches from Nitration to S-nitrosylation (SNO) of proteins [CITATION_11] . In fact, 3-nitrotyrosine levels are reduced and S-nitrosylated proteins are increased at the 10th min of reperfusion. As a matter of fact, it is now believed that SNO of critical proteins plays a very important role in nitricoxide dependent cardioprotection. SNO of many proteins has been found in mitochondria [CITATION_12] (see also below). Nevertheless, PostC increased cardiac 3-nitrotyrosine concentration in the normal but not in the cholesterol-fed heart when measured at the 5th min of reperfusion. These data suggest that a balance between nitrosative stress and S-nitrosylation is involved in the triggering mechanism of PostC and that comorbidities may cause the loss of the cardioprotective effect of PostC, at least in part, via deterioration of the nitrosative trigger [CITATION_13] .",
  "correct_citation": {
